{"title_page": "Aircraft Reactor Experiment", "text_new": "{{short description|Feasibility experiment for aircraft nuclear propulsion}}\n[[File:Aircraft Reactor Experiment during assembly.jpg|300px|thumb|Aircraft Reactor Experiment during assembly showing [[Beryllium oxide|BeO]] [[neutron moderator|moderator]] blocks interlaced with circulating fuel tubes]]\n\nThe '''Aircraft Reactor Experiment (ARE)''' was an experimental [[nuclear reactor]] designed to test the feasibility of fluid-fuel, high-temperature, high-power-density reactors for the propulsion of [[supersonic aircraft]]. It operated between November 8-12, 1954 at the [[Oak Ridge National Laboratory]] (ORNL) with a maximum sustained power of 2.5 [[megawatts]] (MW), and generated a total of 96 MW-hours of energy<ref name=\"ornl1845\"></ref>. \n\nThe ARE was the first reactor to use circulating [[molten salt]] fuel. The hundreds of engineers and scientists working on ARE provided technical data, facilities, equipment, and experience that enabled the broader development of [[molten salt reactors]] as well as [[Liquid_metal_cooled_reactor |liquid metal cooled reactors ]]. \n\n== Background ==\nThe concept of nuclear-powered aircraft was first formally studied in May 1946 by the [[US Army Air Forces]].<ref name=\"nuclearflight\">{{cite book |last1=Gantz |first1=Kenneth |title=Nuclear flight; the United States Air Force programs for atomic jets, missiles, and rockets. |date=1960 |publisher=Duell, Sloan and Pearce |location=New York |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015001555146&view=1up&seq=16 |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> It was supposed that the unique characteristics of nuclear power could be applied to long-range supersonic flight, which was considered highly valuable in terms of military strategy. Challenges in the proposal were understood immediately, and by 1950 the [[United States Atomic Energy Commission|Atomic Energy Commission]] joined with the Air Force to study the possibilities via technology development in the [[Aircraft Nuclear Propulsion]] (ANP) program.\n\nThe ORNL staff of the ANP project decided that technical information and experience needed to support the objective of nuclear-powered flight could most economically be obtained from building and operating the ARE. They considered the task of flying a supersonic airplane on nuclear energy exceedingly complex, and thought more than one experimental reactor may be necessary before sufficient information was obtained to design and construct a reactor for flight. \n\nOriginally, the ARE was conceived as a liquid [[sodium]] metal-cooled [[Beryllium oxide]] (BeO)-moderated solid-fuel reactor. The BeO moderator blocks were purchased with the solid-fuel design in mind. However, concerns regarding [[Nuclear_chain_reaction|chain reaction]] stability related to [[xenon]] in solid fuel at very high temperatures were serious enough to warrant abandoning solid fuel and replacing it with circulating fluid fuel. A fluid-fueled option with molten fluoride salt was worked into the original design.<ref name=\"bettis57\">{{cite journal |last1=Bettis |first1=E.S. |last2=Schroeder |first2=R.W. |last3=Cristy |first3=G.A. |title=The Aircraft Reactor Experiment\u2014Design and Construction |journal=Nuclear Science and Engineering |date=1957 |volume=2 |issue=6 |pages=804\u2013825 |doi=10.13182/NSE57-A35495 }}</ref>\n\n== Reactor ==\n[[File:Aircraft Reactor Experiment Diagram.png|thumb|Aircraft Reactor Experiment Diagram]]\n\n[[File:Aircraft Reactor Experiment cross section.png|thumb|A cross-section of the fluid-fueled Aircraft Reactor Experiment, an experimental nuclear reactor that operated in 1954]]\n\nThe ARE was designed to be a prototype of a 350-megawatt, BeO-moderated, circulating-fuel aircraft reactor. It used a fuel composed of 53.09 mole % NaF, 40.73 mole % ZrF<sub>4</sub>, and 6.18 mole % UF<sub>4</sub>. The reactor was a BeO cylinder with bent tubes directing flowing fuel through the core in both directions. It was surrounded by an [[Inconel]] shell. <ref name=\"ornl1234\">{{cite journal |last1=Cottrell, Editor |first1=W. B. |title=Reactor Program of the Aircraft Nuclear Propulsion Project |journal=Oak Ridge National Lab |date=1952-06-02 |issue=ORNL-1234 |pages=44 |url=https://github.com/openmsr/msr-archive/blob/master/docs/ORNL-1234.pdf |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> The ARE operational life targeted 1000 hours, with as much time as possible at the full power level of 3 megawatts. The design fuel temperature was 1500\u00b0F (816\u00b0C), with a 350\u00b0F (177\u00b0C) temperature rise across the core, though the peak temperature reached 1580\u00b0F (860\u00b0C) in steady operation and peaked at 1620\u00b0F (882\u00b0C) in transients. 46 gallons of fuel flowed through the reactor per minute at a core pressure of about 40 psig (2.76 bar). Sodium was pumped through the reactor at a rate of 150 gallons (568l) per minute with about 50 psig (3.45 bar) of pressure.<ref name=\"ornl1845\"></ref>\n\nThe fuel salt transferred heat to a [[helium]] loop, which then transferred the heat to water. Additionally, the reflector and [[Neutron moderator|moderator]] blocks were cooled with a liquid sodium metal cooling loop, which also transferred heat to helium and then water. \n\nThe reactor contained one [[Startup neutron source|neutron source]] (15 [[Curie|Curies]] of Polonium-Beryllium), 1 regulating rod, and 3 helium-cooled [[boron carbide]] shim rods. The experiment was instrumented with 2 [[fission chambers]], 2 compensated [[ionization chamber|ionization chambers]], and 800 [[thermocouples]]. \n\nThe ARE control system could automatically [[scram]] the reactor based on high [[neutron flux]], fast [[Inhour equation|reactor period]], high reactor exit fuel temperature, low heat exchanger fuel temperature, low fuel flow rate, and loss of offsite power.\n\n== Development Program ==\n[[File:Natural-convection corrosion test loops.jpg|thumb|Natural-convection corrosion test loops used during the Aircraft Nuclear Propulsion project to down-select workable fuel/material combinations]]\n\n[[File:Aircraft Reactor Experiment full-scale mockup.jpg|thumb|Aircraft Reactor Experiment full-scale mockup with clear tubes. Used to shake down filling and draining processes at low temperature]]\n\n[[File:Aircraft Reactor Experiment Equipment Layout.png|thumb|View of the equipment layout in the Aircraft Reactor Experiment]]\n\n[[File:Aircraft Reactor Experiment fuel pump.jpg|thumb|The molten salt fuel pump used in the Aircraft Reactor Experiment]]\n\nThe heat exchanger chamber took up significantly more space than the reactor and dump tank chambers. \n\nThe ambitious goals and military importance of the ANP catalyzed a significant amount of research and development of complex systems in challenging high-temperature, high-[[radiation]] environments. \n\nCorrosion and hot sodium handing studies began in 1950. \n\nInvestigations of the engineering and fabrication problems involved in handling molten fluoride salts began in 1951 and continued through 1954. [[natural convection|Natural-convection]] [[corrosion]] test loops were operated to down-select suitable material and fuel combinations. Subsequent studies in forced-circulation test loops established means to minimize corrosion and [[mass transfer]].\n\nDevelopment of pumps, [[heat exchangers]], [[valves]], [[Pressure_sensor|pressure instrumentation]], and [[cold trap|cold traps]] spanned from late 1951 to summer 1954. Much of the work was based on extensive experience at lower temperature from [[Argonne National Laboratory]] and the [[Knolls Atomic Power Laboratory]]. \n\nTechniques had to be developed concerning the construction, preheating, instrumentation, and insulation of reliable leak-tight high-temperature circuits made of [[Inconel]]. They found that all-welded construction was necessary. \n\nIn all, equipment development in support of high-temperature leak-tight operation lasted about 4 years. <ref name=\"components\">{{cite journal |last1=Savage |first1=H.W. |title=Components of the fused-salt and sodium circuits of the aircraft reactor experiment |journal=Oak Ridge National Lab. |date=1958-09-18 |issue=ORNL-2348 |osti=4308571 }}</ref>\n\nThe ARE Hazard Summary Report<ref name=\"hazards\">{{cite journal |last1=Cottrell |first1=W.B. |title=AIRCRAFT REACTOR EXPERIMENT HAZARDS SUMMARY REPORT |journal=Oak Ridge National Lab. |date=1952-11-24 |issue=ORNL-1407 |osti=4704625 }}</ref> was issued on November 24, 1952. \n\nA low-temperature critical mockup of the reactor was assembled to verify the calculation models. The BeO moderator blocks were fitted with straight tubes filled with a powder mixture to simulate the fuel. Critical mass, regulating rod worth, safety rod worth, neutron flux distributions, and reactivity coefficients of a wide variety of materials were measured. <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Callihan |first1=Dixon |last2=Scott |first2=Dunlap |title=PRELIMINARY CRITICAL ASSEMBLY FOR THE AIRCRAFT REACTOR EXPERIMENT |journal=Oak Ridge National Lab. |date=1953-10-28 |volume=ORNL-1634 |osti=4361426 }}</ref>\n\nConstruction of the test facility building began on July 6, 1951<ref name=\"ornl1234\"></ref>.\n\n[[File:Building plan of the Aircraft Reactor Experiment Building.jpg|thumb|Building plan of the Aircraft Reactor Experiment Building]]\n\n== Operation and Experiments ==\nThe ARE was operated successfully. It became critical with a mass of 32.8 lbs (14.9kg) [[Uranium-235]]. It was very stable as a result of its strong negative [[Fuel temperature coefficient of reactivity|fuel temperature coefficient]] (measured at -9.8e-5 dk/k/\u00b0F). \n\nThe assembly was first sufficiently assembled on August 1, 1954, at which point a three-shift operation commenced for tests. Hot sodium metal was flowed through the system beginning on September 26 to test the process equipment and instrumentation. Problems with the sodium vent and sodium purification systems required lengthy repairs. After several sodium dumps and recharges, carrier salt was introduced to the system on October 25th. Fuel was first added to the reactor on October 30, 1954. Initial [[Criticality_(status)|criticality]] was reached at 3:45 P.M. on November 3, after a painstaking and careful process of adding the [[Enriched uranium|enriched]] fuel. Much of the 4 days was spent removing plugs and repairing leaks in the enrichment line. \n\n[[File:Aircraft Reactor Experiment control room at initial criticality.jpg|thumb|Aircraft Reactor Experiment control room at initial criticality]]\n\nA series of fuel samples were taken periodically. Most notably, they showed an increase in [[Chromium]] content at a rate of 50 ppm/day, indicating rapid corrosion of the fuel pipes. \n\n[[File:Aircraft Reactor Experiment Typical Control Rod Scene.jpg|thumb|Aircraft Reactor Experiment Control Rod Scene during operation: examining charts during rod calibration experiments]]\n\nA series of experiments were performed in the ARE supporting its mission<ref name=\"ornl1845\">{{cite journal |last1=Cottrell |first1=W.B. |title=Operation of the aircraft reactor experiment |journal=Oak Ridge National Lab. |date=1955-09-06 |issue=ORNL-1845 |osti=4237975 }}</ref>.\n\n* Critical experiment\n* Subcritical measurement of reactor temperature coefficient\n* Power determination at 1 Watt (nominal)\n* Regulating rod calibration vs. fuel addition\n* Fuel system characteristics\n* Power determination at 10 Watts\n* Regulating rod calibration vs. reactor period\n* Calibration of shim rod vs. regulating rod\n* Effect of fuel flow on reactivity\n* Low-power measurement of reactor temperature coefficient\n* Adjustment of chamber position\n* Approach to power: 10-kW run\n* Test of off-gas system\n* Approach to power: 100-kW to 1-MW runs\n* High-power measurement of the fuel temperature coefficient\n* High-power measurement of the reactor temperature coefficient\n* Reactor startup on temperature coefficient\n* Sodium temperature coefficient\n* Effect of a dollar of reactivity\n* High-power measurement of reactor temperature coefficient\n* Moderator temperature coefficient\n* Xenon run at full power\n* Reactivity effects of sodium flow\n* Xenon buildup at one-tenth full power\n* Operation at maximum power\n\nAt 4:19 P.M. on November 8, during the ascent to high power, the reactor was shut down due to high airborne radioactivity measurements in the basement. It appeared that the gas fittings to the main fuel pump were leaking [[Nuclear_fission_product|fission-product]] gases and vapors into the pits, and the pits were leaking into the basement through defective seals in some electrical junction panels. A 2-in. pipeline was run from the pits 1000 ft. (305m) south into an uninhabited valley. Portable [[compressors]] and a jet were used to bring the pits to sub-atmospheric pressure for the rest of the experiment. The safety radiation detectors shut down the reactor a few times during restart and were withdrawn to be further away from the reactor. Eventually, the reactor started back up and reached high power. \n\nOn November 12, operation of the reactor was demonstrated to Air Force and ANP personnel who had gathered at ORNL for a quarterly information meeting. [[Load following power plant|Load following]] was demonstrated by turning the blowers on and off. With all operational objectives attained, the decision to cease operation was made. Colonel Clyde D. Gasser was visiting the lab at this time and was invited to officiate the termination of the experiment. At 8:04 P.M., he scrammed the reactor for the last time. \n\n[[File:Final shutdown of the Aircraft Reactor Experiment.jpg|thumb|Final shutdown of the Aircraft Reactor Experiment. Colonel Gasser of the Air Force was visiting at the time and had the honor of scramming the reactor]]\n\nMuch information was published about the operation of the reactor, including detailed experimental logs, power traces, and a total of 33 lessons learned.<ref name=\"ornl1845\"></ref>\n\n== Decommissioning ==\n[[File:Aircraft Reactor Experiment heat exchanger pit decommissioning.jpg|thumb|The heat exchanger pit of the ARE during decommissioning]]\n\n[[File:Aircraft Reactor Experiment on truck.jpg|thumb|Aircraft Reactor Experiment on truck on way to burial ground]]\n\nBetween shutdown and fuel dumping, the operating personnel were required to wear gas masks due to the high level of airborne radioactivity, which was due to a offgas leak, which was never exactly located.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cottrell |first1=W.B. |title=DISASSEMBLY AND POSTOPERATIVE EXAMINATION OF THE AIRCRAFT REACTOR EXPERIMENT |journal=Oak Ridge National Lab. |date=1958-04-15 |volume=ORNL-1868 |osti=4223435 }}</ref>. On November 13th, the fuel was transferred to the fuel dump tank. Pressurized carrier salt flushed the pipes and diluted the dump tank. Flush salt was heated to 100\u00b0F above the system temperature and pumped through the fuel channels. Operators observed the thermocouples to ensure flush salt flowed in all channels. \n\nAfter the fuel dump, the operating personnel had to evacuate the building for 1 hour after gas from the fuel purge operation which had been discharged out the stack descended and entered the ventilators on the building roof. The sodium system was drained without incident. \n\nTwo flat 6 ft. by 4 ft. [[Lead_shielding|lead shields]] with 2 inch thickness were suspended in the heat exchanger cell to protect decommissioning personnel from radiation from the fuel systems. \n\nWater lines were cut first. Then, sodium lines were cut with hack saws and immediately sealed with several layers of masking tape. The sodium pump was cleaned and the impeller was removed for examination. When the sodium pump and heat exchanger were removed, the radiation field in the room increased to 600 [[Roentgen_equivalent_man|mrem]]/hr. The equipment had been shielding the area from the fuel system radiation.\n\nThe fuel system was carefully dismantled starting in February, 1955. The main fuel pump bowl surveyed at 900 mrem/hr at 5 ft. A portable grinder that could be operated from within a lead box was built to cut the fuel lines near the reactor can. Once it was free, the reactor was moved to storage and later to a burial ground. The fuel in the dump tank was slated to be reprocessed.\n\nAbout 60 samples of equipment and material were taken for detailed analysis and examination. Metallographic, [[Neutron activation analysis|activation]], visual, [[Stereoscopy|stereophotographic]], and leak tests were performed. \n\n== Follow-up ==\n[[File:Aircraft Reactor Test construction.jpg|thumb|Heavy construction to fit the ART in the building where ARE had been]]\nAfter the ARE operated, the ANP project moved on with plans to build a larger experiment, the 60 MW Aircraft Reactor Test (ART).<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fraas |first1=A.P. |title=Design report on the Aircraft Reactor Test |journal=Oak Ridge National Lab |date=1956-12-21 |volume=ORNL-2095 |url=http://moltensalt.org/references/static/downloads/pdf/ORNL-2095.pdf |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> The ART was to be a NaF-ZrF<sub>4</sub>-UF<sub>4</sub>-fueled, Be-moderated, Be-reflected core with sodium metal as the reflector coolant and NaK as the secondary coolant. Its shield was made of lead and borated water. \n\nBuilding 7503 at ORNL was significantly re-excavated in an extension project including new deep excavations to accommodate the ART, but the program was cancelled before the new experiment was performed.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ferguson |first1=W.F. |title=TERMINATION REPORT FOR CONSTRUCTION OF THE ART FACILITY |journal=Oak Ridge National Lab |date=1958-11-21 |volume=ORNL-2465 |url=https://github.com/openmsr/msr-archive/blob/master/docs/ORNL-2465.pdf |accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref> The building and facilities later went on to house the [[Molten Salt Reactor Experiment]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n\n<!--- Categories --->\n\n[[Category:Nuclear propulsion]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Feasibility experiment for aircraft nuclear propulsion}}\n[[File:Aircraft Reactor Experiment during assembly.jpg|300px|thumb|Aircraft Reactor Experiment during assembly showing [[Beryllium oxide|BeO]] [[neutron moderator|moderator]] blocks interlaced with circulating fuel tubes]]\n\nThe '''Aircraft Reactor Experiment (ARE)''' was an experimental [[nuclear reactor]] designed to test the feasibility of fluid-fuel, high-temperature, high-power-density reactors for the propulsion of [[supersonic aircraft]]. It operated between November 8-12, 1954 at the [[Oak Ridge National Laboratory]] (ORNL) with a maximum sustained power of 2.5 [[megawatts]] (MW), and generated a total of 96 MW-hours of energy<ref name=\"ornl1845\"></ref>. \n\nThe ARE was the first reactor to use circulating [[molten salt]] fuel. The hundreds of engineers and scientists working on ARE provided technical data, facilities, equipment, and experience that enabled to the broader development of [[molten salt reactors]] as well as [[Liquid_metal_cooled_reactor |liquid metal cooled reactors ]]. \n\n== Background ==\nThe concept of nuclear-powered aircraft was first formally studied in May 1946 by the [[US Army Air Forces]].<ref name=\"nuclearflight\">{{cite book |last1=Gantz |first1=Kenneth |title=Nuclear flight; the United States Air Force programs for atomic jets, missiles, and rockets. |date=1960 |publisher=Duell, Sloan and Pearce |location=New York |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015001555146&view=1up&seq=16 |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> It was supposed that the unique characteristics of nuclear power could be applied to long-range supersonic flight, which was considered highly valuable in terms of military strategy. Challenges in the proposal were understood immediately, and by 1950 the [[United States Atomic Energy Commission|Atomic Energy Commission]] joined with the Air Force to study the possibilities via technology development in the [[Aircraft Nuclear Propulsion]] (ANP) program.\n\nThe ORNL staff of the ANP project decided that technical information and experience needed to support the objective of nuclear-powered flight could most economically be obtained from building and operating the ARE. They considered the task of flying a supersonic airplane on nuclear energy exceedingly complex, and thought more than one experimental reactor may be necessary before sufficient information was obtained to design and construct a reactor for flight. \n\nOriginally, the ARE was conceived as a liquid [[sodium]] metal-cooled [[Beryllium oxide]] (BeO)-moderated solid-fuel reactor. The BeO moderator blocks were purchased with the solid-fuel design in mind. However, concerns regarding [[Nuclear_chain_reaction|chain reaction]] stability related to [[xenon]] in solid fuel at very high temperatures were serious enough to warrant abandoning solid fuel and replacing it with circulating fluid fuel. A fluid-fueled option with molten fluoride salt was worked into the original design.<ref name=\"bettis57\">{{cite journal |last1=Bettis |first1=E.S. |last2=Schroeder |first2=R.W. |last3=Cristy |first3=G.A. |title=The Aircraft Reactor Experiment\u2014Design and Construction |journal=Nuclear Science and Engineering |date=1957 |volume=2 |issue=6 |pages=804\u2013825 |doi=10.13182/NSE57-A35495 }}</ref>\n\n== Reactor ==\n[[File:Aircraft Reactor Experiment Diagram.png|thumb|Aircraft Reactor Experiment Diagram]]\n\n[[File:Aircraft Reactor Experiment cross section.png|thumb|A cross-section of the fluid-fueled Aircraft Reactor Experiment, an experimental nuclear reactor that operated in 1954]]\n\nThe ARE was designed to be a prototype of a 350-megawatt, BeO-moderated, circulating-fuel aircraft reactor. It used a fuel composed of 53.09 mole % NaF, 40.73 mole % ZrF<sub>4</sub>, and 6.18 mole % UF<sub>4</sub>. The reactor was a BeO cylinder with bent tubes directing flowing fuel through the core in both directions. It was surrounded by an [[Inconel]] shell. <ref name=\"ornl1234\">{{cite journal |last1=Cottrell, Editor |first1=W. B. |title=Reactor Program of the Aircraft Nuclear Propulsion Project |journal=Oak Ridge National Lab |date=1952-06-02 |issue=ORNL-1234 |pages=44 |url=https://github.com/openmsr/msr-archive/blob/master/docs/ORNL-1234.pdf |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> The ARE operational life targeted 1000 hours, with as much time as possible at the full power level of 3 megawatts. The design fuel temperature was 1500\u00b0F (816\u00b0C), with a 350\u00b0F (177\u00b0C) temperature rise across the core, though the peak temperature reached 1580\u00b0F (860\u00b0C) in steady operation and peaked at 1620\u00b0F (882\u00b0C) in transients. 46 gallons of fuel flowed through the reactor per minute at a core pressure of about 40 psig (2.76 bar). Sodium was pumped through the reactor at a rate of 150 gallons (568l) per minute with about 50 psig (3.45 bar) of pressure.<ref name=\"ornl1845\"></ref>\n\nThe fuel salt transferred heat to a [[helium]] loop, which then transferred the heat to water. Additionally, the reflector and [[Neutron moderator|moderator]] blocks were cooled with a liquid sodium metal cooling loop, which also transferred heat to helium and then water. \n\nThe reactor contained one [[Startup neutron source|neutron source]] (15 [[Curie|Curies]] of Polonium-Beryllium), 1 regulating rod, and 3 helium-cooled [[boron carbide]] shim rods. The experiment was instrumented with 2 [[fission chambers]], 2 compensated [[ionization chamber|ionization chambers]], and 800 [[thermocouples]]. \n\nThe ARE control system could automatically [[scram]] the reactor based on high [[neutron flux]], fast [[Inhour equation|reactor period]], high reactor exit fuel temperature, low heat exchanger fuel temperature, low fuel flow rate, and loss of offsite power.\n\n== Development Program ==\n[[File:Natural-convection corrosion test loops.jpg|thumb|Natural-convection corrosion test loops used during the Aircraft Nuclear Propulsion project to down-select workable fuel/material combinations]]\n\n[[File:Aircraft Reactor Experiment full-scale mockup.jpg|thumb|Aircraft Reactor Experiment full-scale mockup with clear tubes. Used to shake down filling and draining processes at low temperature]]\n\n[[File:Aircraft Reactor Experiment Equipment Layout.png|thumb|View of the equipment layout in the Aircraft Reactor Experiment]]\n\n[[File:Aircraft Reactor Experiment fuel pump.jpg|thumb|The molten salt fuel pump used in the Aircraft Reactor Experiment]]\n\nThe heat exchanger chamber took up significantly more space than the reactor and dump tank chambers. \n\nThe ambitious goals and military importance of the ANP catalyzed a significant amount of research and development of complex systems in challenging high-temperature, high-[[radiation]] environments. \n\nCorrosion and hot sodium handing studies began in 1950. \n\nInvestigations of the engineering and fabrication problems involved in handling molten fluoride salts began in 1951 and continued through 1954. [[natural convection|Natural-convection]] [[corrosion]] test loops were operated to down-select suitable material and fuel combinations. Subsequent studies in forced-circulation test loops established means to minimize corrosion and [[mass transfer]].\n\nDevelopment of pumps, [[heat exchangers]], [[valves]], [[Pressure_sensor|pressure instrumentation]], and [[cold trap|cold traps]] spanned from late 1951 to summer 1954. Much of the work was based on extensive experience at lower temperature from [[Argonne National Laboratory]] and the [[Knolls Atomic Power Laboratory]]. \n\nTechniques had to be developed concerning the construction, preheating, instrumentation, and insulation of reliable leak-tight high-temperature circuits made of [[Inconel]]. They found that all-welded construction was necessary. \n\nIn all, equipment development in support of high-temperature leak-tight operation lasted about 4 years. <ref name=\"components\">{{cite journal |last1=Savage |first1=H.W. |title=Components of the fused-salt and sodium circuits of the aircraft reactor experiment |journal=Oak Ridge National Lab. |date=1958-09-18 |issue=ORNL-2348 |osti=4308571 }}</ref>\n\nThe ARE Hazard Summary Report<ref name=\"hazards\">{{cite journal |last1=Cottrell |first1=W.B. |title=AIRCRAFT REACTOR EXPERIMENT HAZARDS SUMMARY REPORT |journal=Oak Ridge National Lab. |date=1952-11-24 |issue=ORNL-1407 |osti=4704625 }}</ref> was issued on November 24, 1952. \n\nA low-temperature critical mockup of the reactor was assembled to verify the calculation models. The BeO moderator blocks were fitted with straight tubes filled with a powder mixture to simulate the fuel. Critical mass, regulating rod worth, safety rod worth, neutron flux distributions, and reactivity coefficients of a wide variety of materials were measured. <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Callihan |first1=Dixon |last2=Scott |first2=Dunlap |title=PRELIMINARY CRITICAL ASSEMBLY FOR THE AIRCRAFT REACTOR EXPERIMENT |journal=Oak Ridge National Lab. |date=1953-10-28 |volume=ORNL-1634 |osti=4361426 }}</ref>\n\nConstruction of the test facility building began on July 6, 1951<ref name=\"ornl1234\"></ref>.\n\n[[File:Building plan of the Aircraft Reactor Experiment Building.jpg|thumb|Building plan of the Aircraft Reactor Experiment Building]]\n\n== Operation and Experiments ==\nThe ARE was operated successfully. It became critical with a mass of 32.8 lbs (14.9kg) [[Uranium-235]]. It was very stable as a result of its strong negative [[Fuel temperature coefficient of reactivity|fuel temperature coefficient]] (measured at -9.8e-5 dk/k/\u00b0F). \n\nThe assembly was first sufficiently assembled on August 1, 1954, at which point a three-shift operation commenced for tests. Hot sodium metal was flowed through the system beginning on September 26 to test the process equipment and instrumentation. Problems with the sodium vent and sodium purification systems required lengthy repairs. After several sodium dumps and recharges, carrier salt was introduced to the system on October 25th. Fuel was first added to the reactor on October 30, 1954. Initial [[Criticality_(status)|criticality]] was reached at 3:45 P.M. on November 3, after a painstaking and careful process of adding the [[Enriched uranium|enriched]] fuel. Much of the 4 days was spent removing plugs and repairing leaks in the enrichment line. \n\n[[File:Aircraft Reactor Experiment control room at initial criticality.jpg|thumb|Aircraft Reactor Experiment control room at initial criticality]]\n\nA series of fuel samples were taken periodically. Most notably, they showed an increase in [[Chromium]] content at a rate of 50 ppm/day, indicating rapid corrosion of the fuel pipes. \n\n[[File:Aircraft Reactor Experiment Typical Control Rod Scene.jpg|thumb|Aircraft Reactor Experiment Control Rod Scene during operation: examining charts during rod calibration experiments]]\n\nA series of experiments were performed in the ARE supporting its mission<ref name=\"ornl1845\">{{cite journal |last1=Cottrell |first1=W.B. |title=Operation of the aircraft reactor experiment |journal=Oak Ridge National Lab. |date=1955-09-06 |issue=ORNL-1845 |osti=4237975 }}</ref>.\n\n* Critical experiment\n* Subcritical measurement of reactor temperature coefficient\n* Power determination at 1 Watt (nominal)\n* Regulating rod calibration vs. fuel addition\n* Fuel system characteristics\n* Power determination at 10 Watts\n* Regulating rod calibration vs. reactor period\n* Calibration of shim rod vs. regulating rod\n* Effect of fuel flow on reactivity\n* Low-power measurement of reactor temperature coefficient\n* Adjustment of chamber position\n* Approach to power: 10-kW run\n* Test of off-gas system\n* Approach to power: 100-kW to 1-MW runs\n* High-power measurement of the fuel temperature coefficient\n* High-power measurement of the reactor temperature coefficient\n* Reactor startup on temperature coefficient\n* Sodium temperature coefficient\n* Effect of a dollar of reactivity\n* High-power measurement of reactor temperature coefficient\n* Moderator temperature coefficient\n* Xenon run at full power\n* Reactivity effects of sodium flow\n* Xenon buildup at one-tenth full power\n* Operation at maximum power\n\nAt 4:19 P.M. on November 8, during the ascent to high power, the reactor was shut down due to high airborne radioactivity measurements in the basement. It appeared that the gas fittings to the main fuel pump were leaking [[Nuclear_fission_product|fission-product]] gases and vapors into the pits, and the pits were leaking into the basement through defective seals in some electrical junction panels. A 2-in. pipeline was run from the pits 1000 ft. (305m) south into an uninhabited valley. Portable [[compressors]] and a jet were used to bring the pits to sub-atmospheric pressure for the rest of the experiment. The safety radiation detectors shut down the reactor a few times during restart and were withdrawn to be further away from the reactor. Eventually, the reactor started back up and reached high power. \n\nOn November 12, operation of the reactor was demonstrated to Air Force and ANP personnel who had gathered at ORNL for a quarterly information meeting. [[Load following power plant|Load following]] was demonstrated by turning the blowers on and off. With all operational objectives attained, the decision to cease operation was made. Colonel Clyde D. Gasser was visiting the lab at this time and was invited to officiate the termination of the experiment. At 8:04 P.M., he scrammed the reactor for the last time. \n\n[[File:Final shutdown of the Aircraft Reactor Experiment.jpg|thumb|Final shutdown of the Aircraft Reactor Experiment. Colonel Gasser of the Air Force was visiting at the time and had the honor of scramming the reactor]]\n\nMuch information was published about the operation of the reactor, including detailed experimental logs, power traces, and a total of 33 lessons learned.<ref name=\"ornl1845\"></ref>\n\n== Decommissioning ==\n[[File:Aircraft Reactor Experiment heat exchanger pit decommissioning.jpg|thumb|The heat exchanger pit of the ARE during decommissioning]]\n\n[[File:Aircraft Reactor Experiment on truck.jpg|thumb|Aircraft Reactor Experiment on truck on way to burial ground]]\n\nBetween shutdown and fuel dumping, the operating personnel were required to wear gas masks due to the high level of airborne radioactivity, which was due to a offgas leak, which was never exactly located.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cottrell |first1=W.B. |title=DISASSEMBLY AND POSTOPERATIVE EXAMINATION OF THE AIRCRAFT REACTOR EXPERIMENT |journal=Oak Ridge National Lab. |date=1958-04-15 |volume=ORNL-1868 |osti=4223435 }}</ref>. On November 13th, the fuel was transferred to the fuel dump tank. Pressurized carrier salt flushed the pipes and diluted the dump tank. Flush salt was heated to 100\u00b0F above the system temperature and pumped through the fuel channels. Operators observed the thermocouples to ensure flush salt flowed in all channels. \n\nAfter the fuel dump, the operating personnel had to evacuate the building for 1 hour after gas from the fuel purge operation which had been discharged out the stack descended and entered the ventilators on the building roof. The sodium system was drained without incident. \n\nTwo flat 6 ft. by 4 ft. [[Lead_shielding|lead shields]] with 2 inch thickness were suspended in the heat exchanger cell to protect decommissioning personnel from radiation from the fuel systems. \n\nWater lines were cut first. Then, sodium lines were cut with hack saws and immediately sealed with several layers of masking tape. The sodium pump was cleaned and the impeller was removed for examination. When the sodium pump and heat exchanger were removed, the radiation field in the room increased to 600 [[Roentgen_equivalent_man|mrem]]/hr. The equipment had been shielding the area from the fuel system radiation.\n\nThe fuel system was carefully dismantled starting in February, 1955. The main fuel pump bowl surveyed at 900 mrem/hr at 5 ft. A portable grinder that could be operated from within a lead box was built to cut the fuel lines near the reactor can. Once it was free, the reactor was moved to storage and later to a burial ground. The fuel in the dump tank was slated to be reprocessed.\n\nAbout 60 samples of equipment and material were taken for detailed analysis and examination. Metallographic, [[Neutron activation analysis|activation]], visual, [[Stereoscopy|stereophotographic]], and leak tests were performed. \n\n== Follow-up ==\n[[File:Aircraft Reactor Test construction.jpg|thumb|Heavy construction to fit the ART in the building where ARE had been]]\nAfter the ARE operated, the ANP project moved on with plans to build a larger experiment, the 60 MW Aircraft Reactor Test (ART).<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fraas |first1=A.P. |title=Design report on the Aircraft Reactor Test |journal=Oak Ridge National Lab |date=1956-12-21 |volume=ORNL-2095 |url=http://moltensalt.org/references/static/downloads/pdf/ORNL-2095.pdf |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> The ART was to be a NaF-ZrF<sub>4</sub>-UF<sub>4</sub>-fueled, Be-moderated, Be-reflected core with sodium metal as the reflector coolant and NaK as the secondary coolant. Its shield was made of lead and borated water. \n\nBuilding 7503 at ORNL was significantly re-excavated in an extension project including new deep excavations to accommodate the ART, but the program was cancelled before the new experiment was performed.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ferguson |first1=W.F. |title=TERMINATION REPORT FOR CONSTRUCTION OF THE ART FACILITY |journal=Oak Ridge National Lab |date=1958-11-21 |volume=ORNL-2465 |url=https://github.com/openmsr/msr-archive/blob/master/docs/ORNL-2465.pdf |accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref> The building and facilities later went on to house the [[Molten Salt Reactor Experiment]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n\n<!--- Categories --->\n\n[[Category:Nuclear propulsion]]\n", "name_user": "Ntouran", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aircraft_Reactor_Experiment"}
